 fascinating look at the relationship between popular music in China and broad cultural, social, and political changes that are taking place there. Baranovitch's sources include formal interviews and conversations conducted with some of China's most prominent rock and pop musicians and music critics, with ordinary people who provide lay perspectives on popular music culture, and with others involved in the music industry and in academia. Baranovitch also observed recording sessions, concerts, and dance parties, and draws upon TV broadcasts and many publications in Chinese about popular music.keywords: Ethnicity  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusique populairexAspect politiquexChine. 0aMusique populairexAspect socialxChine. 0aPopular musicxPolitical aspectsxChina. 0aPopular musicxPolitical aspectszChina. 0aPopular musicxSocial aspectsxChina. 0aPopular musicxSocial aspectszChina. 4aGenres & Styles. 4aMusic. 4aPop Vocal. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Pop Vocal.2bisacsh1 aBaranovitch, Nimrod, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023450540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093653940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936539423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936539/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles